@page "/impact"

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HERO (dark green) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="hero">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h1>Our Impact</h1>
        <p>
            Ripple is a proof‑of‑concept project created for a college honors program. While the website 
            models how a real aquaponics‑based nonprofit could address food insecurity in Chicagoland, 
            Ripple is not an active organization. This page illustrates the potential impact such a system 
            could have if implemented in a real community setting.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- FOOD INSECURITY (pale coral) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-coral">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Food Insecurity in Chicago</h2>
        <p>
            Many Chicago‑area households face rising food costs, limited access to fresh produce, and 
            structural barriers that contribute to food insecurity. These challenges make the region an 
            ideal case study for exploring sustainable, year‑round food production models.
        </p>
        <p>
            In this project, Ripple is used as a hypothetical example of how aquaponics could help close 
            this gap by producing fresh, nutrient‑dense food locally and consistently.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-blue"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HOW RIPPLE HELPS (pale blue) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-blue">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>How Ripple Helps (Modeled Impact)</h2>

        <div class="impact-grid">

            <div class="impact-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-calendar impact-icon"></i>
                <h3>Year‑Round Food Production</h3>
                <p>
                    The conceptual aquaponics system grows leafy greens and tilapia continuously, 
                    demonstrating how controlled‑environment agriculture can operate regardless of season.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="impact-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-truck impact-icon"></i>
                <h3>Local Distribution</h3>
                <p>
                    In this model, food is distributed through food pantries, shelters, and community 
                    partners. This distribution network is hypothetical and included to show how a real 
                    nonprofit might serve neighborhoods facing food insecurity.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="impact-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-leaf impact-icon"></i>
                <h3>Sustainable Farming</h3>
                <p>
                    Aquaponics uses up to <strong>90% less water</strong>, requires no soil, and minimizes 
                    chemical inputs. These sustainability benefits are part of the system design explored 
                    in this academic project.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="impact-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-people-group impact-icon"></i>
                <h3>Community Engagement</h3>
                <p>
                    Volunteers, students, and local residents are imagined as participants in planting, 
                    harvesting, packaging, and outreach. These roles are conceptual and demonstrate how 
                    community involvement could look in a real implementation.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="impact-card">
                <i class="fa-solid fa-flask impact-icon"></i>
                <h3>Education & Research</h3>
                <p>
                    The project includes a modeled research area to illustrate how innovation in aquaponics 
                    could be supported and shared with the broader community.
                </p>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT (dark green) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="why-aquaponics">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Environmental Impact</h2>
        <p>
            Aquaponics reduces environmental strain by conserving water, reducing land use, lowering carbon 
            footprint, minimizing chemical inputs, and supporting biodiversity. The project also models 
            features like skylights, efficient LED lighting, and energy‑saving design choices to demonstrate 
            how a real facility might operate sustainably.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-blue"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- SDG INTRO (pale coral) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-coral">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2><i class="fa-solid fa-globe"></i> What Are the UN Sustainable Development Goals?</h2>
        <p>
            The United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) are a global framework designed to 
            promote a healthier, more equitable, and more sustainable future. Ripple’s conceptual aquaponics 
            model aligns with three of these goals by demonstrating how local food production, efficient 
            resource use, and community‑centered design could support real‑world sustainability efforts.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-blue"></div>

<!-- ===================================================== -->
<!-- SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT GOALS (pale blue) -->
<!-- ===================================================== -->
<section class="pale-blue">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Supporting the UN Sustainable Development Goals</h2>
        <p>
            Although Ripple is a conceptual project, its modeled design reflects how a real aquaponics‑based 
            initiative could strengthen food systems, support communities, and promote responsible resource 
            use. These three SDGs highlight the potential impact.
        </p>

        <div class="impact-grid">

            <!-- SDG 2 -->
            <div class="flip-card">
                <input type="checkbox" id="sdg2" class="flip-checkbox" />
                <label for="sdg2" class="flip-card-label">
                    <div class="flip-card-inner">

                        <div class="flip-card-front">
                            <i class="fa-solid fa-bowl-food"></i>
                            <h3>SDG 2: Zero Hunger</h3>
                        </div>

                        <div class="flip-card-back">
                            <h3>SDG 2: Zero Hunger</h3>
                            <p>
                                The modeled system shows how communities could grow fresh vegetables and fish locally 
                                using far fewer resources than traditional agriculture. By producing nutritious, 
                                pesticide‑free food year‑round, aquaponics offers a resilient way to supplement local 
                                food supplies and improve access to healthy options.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                    </div>
                </label>
            </div>

            <!-- SDG 11 -->
            <div class="flip-card">
                <input type="checkbox" id="sdg11" class="flip-checkbox" />
                <label for="sdg11" class="flip-card-label">
                    <div class="flip-card-inner">

                        <div class="flip-card-front">
                            <i class="fa-solid fa-city"></i>
                            <h3>SDG 11: Sustainable Cities & Communities</h3>
                        </div>

                        <div class="flip-card-back">
                            <h3>SDG 11: Sustainable Cities & Communities</h3>
                            <p>
                                Urban areas often face high food costs and limited access to fresh produce. Ripple’s 
                                conceptual model demonstrates how local aquaponics facilities could reduce transportation 
                                needs, strengthen community food networks, and provide a scalable approach to addressing 
                                food deserts and supply chain disruptions.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                    </div>
                </label>
            </div>

            <!-- SDG 12 -->
            <div class="flip-card">
                <input type="checkbox" id="sdg12" class="flip-checkbox" />
                <label for="sdg12" class="flip-card-label">
                    <div class="flip-card-inner">

                        <div class="flip-card-front">
                            <i class="fa-solid fa-recycle"></i>
                            <h3>SDG 12: Responsible Consumption & Production</h3>
                        </div>

                        <div class="flip-card-back">
                            <h3>SDG 12: Responsible Consumption & Production</h3>
                            <p>
                                By shortening supply chains and growing food close to where it is distributed, aquaponics 
                                can help reduce waste and lower emissions from long‑distance transport. The modeled system 
                                also highlights efficient use of water, energy, and space—key components of sustainable 
                                production practices.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                    </div>
                </label>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- RESILIENT FUTURE (dark green) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="why-aquaponics">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Building a More Resilient Future</h2>
        <p>
            While aquaponics is not a full replacement for traditional agriculture, it offers a powerful 
            supplement — especially in urban environments. By producing food locally, sustainably, and 
            predictably, systems like the one modeled in Ripple could help communities become more resilient 
            to climate change, supply chain disruptions, rising food costs, and seasonal shortages.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>
